{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0ad6eadb-7890-4d2a-8515-7a08f228dd27","content":"\n\nIn .NET MAUI, `Application.OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` **still exist** and work the same way. However, the recommended approach is to use the **`Window` lifecycle events** for more granular control:\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (Window) |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Window.Created` / override `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Window.Stopped` / override `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Window.Resumed` / override `OnResumed()` |\n\n**Option 1 — Override `CreateWindow` in `App`:**\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Subclass `Window`:**\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated() { /* ... */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped() { /* ... */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed() { /* ... */ }\n}\n```\n\nThe `Window`-based approach is preferred because MAUI supports **multi-window apps**, so lifecycle is per-window rather than per-application.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"77299676-0441-42d1-ad7f-09dad6d7f638","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`. The `Application` class in MAUI still has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` — but the recommended approach is to use the `Window` lifecycle methods:\n\n- `Window.Created` / `OnCreated`\n\n\n- `Window.Stopped` / `OnStopped`  \n- `Window.Resumed` / `OnResumed`\n- `Window.Destroying` / `OnDestroying`\n\nYou can either override `CreateWindow()` and return a custom `Window` subclass, or work directly with the lifecycle events on the `Window` class. The key mappings are `OnStart` maps to `Window.Created`, `OnSleep` maps to `Window.Stopped`, and `OnResume` maps to `Window.Resumed`.","outputTokens":842},"id":"88179c27-2ee7-4f06-bbca-cf6e978b90e9","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:47:16.449Z","parentId":"c3792eb4-4353-46a7-8b35-f5011e8a3f48"}
